city=data$city 
time=as.POSIXct(data$time, origin = "1970-01-01") # convert unix timestamp to date
main=data$main 
wind=data$wind 
clouds=data$clouds 
weather=bind_rows(data$weather)

The first step is to transform the data into a form that can be easily analysed. Notice that: 1.The time variable in the original dataset is unix timestamp, I changed it back to date time format to verify that these data are on taken at the same time (2019 April 5th 12.05pm-12.08pm); 2. The weather table was a list of 209,579 dataframes, hence I first combined them into one dataframe for easier analysis.

2. Combine variables into one data frame

dat=cbind(city, time, main, wind, clouds) 
# rename some variables
dat= dat %>%
 rename( 
 cityname = name, 
 clouds = all 
 )

3. Data Visualisation

First, I plotted the correlation matrix between variables and then explore the relationship in details.

Correlation Matrix Plot

library(corrplot)
## corrplot 0.89 loaded
correlations <- cor(dat[,c(5:6,8:15)], use="pairwise", method="spearman") 
corrplot(correlations, tl.srt = 30,title='Correlation Matrix', mar=c(0,1,1,0), method="number", type="upper", order="hclust")

It can be seen that: 1. Temperature has moderate negative relationship with latitude, moderate positive relationship with longitude and slightly negative relationship with cloudliness. 2. Humidity has moderate positive relationship with cloudliness and slightly negative relationship with wind speed. Next, we look into the correlation in more details

Temperature

library(ggplot2) 
## Warning: package 'ggplot2' was built under R version 3.6.3
jet.colors <- colorRampPalette(c("#00007F", "blue", "#007FFF", "cyan", "#7FFF7F", "yellow", "#FF7F00", "red", "#7F0000")) 
p=ggplot() + 
 geom_tile(data = dat, aes(x=round(coord$lon), y=round(coord$lat), fill=temp)) + scale_fill_gradientn(colors = jet.colors(7), limits = c(220, 320)) + 
 coord_quickmap() 
p+labs(title="Temperature plot",  x ="Longitude ", y = "Latitude")

# temperature map with continents added
library(maps) 
## Warning: package 'maps' was built under R version 3.6.3
p+ borders() +labs(title="Temperature plot in global map", 
x ="Longitude ", y = "Latitude")

It can be seen that the temperature is higher for countries closer to equator. It peaks at around 0-100 longitude and 0-30 latitude.

Humidity

ggplot(data=dat, aes(x=humidity,y=clouds))+geom_point()

It can be seen that when humidity is low there tends to be less clouds, when humidity is high there tends to be more clouds.

ggplot(data=dat, aes(x=coord$lat,y=humidity,color=temp)) +geom_point() +labs(title="Humidity plot",  x ="Latitude ", y = "humidity")

ggplot(data=dat, aes(x=coord$lat,y=clouds,color=temp)) +geom_point() +labs(title="Cloud plot", 
x ="Latitude ", y = "clouds")

Humidity and cloudliness are relatively consistent across all latitudes.

Wind

It seems that wind speed is not very different for latitudes/longitudes, except for the fact that highest wind speeds mostly occurs at high latitude.
